e of <i>roue</i> ‘wheel’). Compare   Wheeler  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>rouer(e)</i> ‘rower, oarsman’. Compare   Rother  .","German (<b>Röwer</b>): unexplained."]},{"name":"Wheelwright","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>whelewright(e)</i>, <i>whelrihte</i> ‘wheelwright, maker of wheels and wheeled vehicles’ (Old English <i>hwēol</i> + <i>wyrhta</i>). See also   Wheeler  .","History: John Wheelwright (<i>c.</i> 1592–1679), clergyman, came to Boston, MA, from Lincolnshire, England in 1636. He was banished from Massachusettes for his support of his sister-in-law, Anne Hutchinson, in the antinomian controversy; he set up a community at Exeter, NH."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Wheeler was born in 1348, in Bedfordshire, England, his father, Lord Richard Wheeler II, was 48 and his mother, Jane Ann Londonderry, was 47. He married Sussanah Milk in 1375, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 7 October 1397, in Frampton Cotterell, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 49, and was buried in Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"1348–7 October 1397":"1348–7. oktoober 1397","1348–1397":"1348–1397","1347–1400":"1347–1400","1375–1420":"1375–1420","1300–1380":"1300–1380","1302–1375":"1302–1375","1348":"1348","7 October 1397":"7. oktoober 1397","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1400":"1400",